but first i want to complain about this:

    curl_setopt_array($ch1, array(
        CURLOPT_URL =&gt; &quot;url&quot;,
        CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER =&gt; true,
        CURLOPT_ENCODING =&gt; &quot;&quot;,
        CURLOPT_MAXREDIRS =&gt; 10,
        CURLOPT_TIMEOUT =&gt; 30,
        CURLOPT_HTTP_VERSION =&gt; CURL_HTTP_VERSION_1_1,
        CURLOPT_CUSTOMREQUEST =&gt; &quot;POST&quot;,
        CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS =&gt; &#39;{&quot;userip&quot;:&quot;&#39; . $_REQUEST[&#39;ip&#39;] . &#39;&quot;,&quot;firstname&quot;:&quot;&#39; . $_REQUEST[&#39;firstname&#39;] . &#39;&quot;, &quot;lastname&quot;:&quot;&#39; . $_REQUEST[&#39;lastName&#39;] . &#39;&quot;, &quot;email&quot;:&quot;&#39; . $_REQUEST[&#39;email&#39;] . &#39;&quot;, &quot;password&quot;:&quot;&#39; . $_REQUEST[&#39;password&#39;] . &#39;&quot;, &quot;phone&quot;:&quot;&#39; . $_REQUEST[&#39;phonenumber&#39;] . &#39;&quot;, &quot;prefix&quot;:&quot;&#39; . $_REQUEST[&#39;phonecode&#39;] . &#39;&quot; }&#39;,
    ));

1: use CURLOPT_POST, not CURLOPT_CUSTOMREQUEST (for one, it&#39;s just the right thing to do, and libcurl actually understands that you want a POST request then, rather than some nonstandard request)

2: what do you think will happen if `$_REQUEST[&#39;password&#39;]` includes `&quot;` ? it would corrupt your json, making it unparsable...

3: via manipulating $_REQUEST[&#39;password&#39;] (or any other variable there), your code is vulnerable to JSON injection, hackers can for example spoof their IP, giving a fake `userip` (if you don&#39;t know what JSON injection is, it&#39;s kindof like [SQL Injection](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SQL_injection), but they can inject JSON data (like a spoofed userip) instead of SQL commands, looks like:  `{&quot;data&quot;:&quot;real_data&quot;,&quot;data&quot;:&quot;evil_hacker_injected_version_of_data_that_will_replace_it_because_it_is_the_last_definition_of_data&quot;}`  )

use json_encode() to safely create your json, like this: 

    curl_setopt_array($ch1, array(
        CURLOPT_URL =&gt; &quot;url&quot;,
        CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER =&gt; true,
        CURLOPT_ENCODING =&gt; &quot;&quot;,
        CURLOPT_MAXREDIRS =&gt; 10,
        CURLOPT_TIMEOUT =&gt; 30,
        CURLOPT_HTTP_VERSION =&gt; CURL_HTTP_VERSION_1_1,
        CURLOPT_POST =&gt; 1,
        CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS =&gt; json_encode(array(
            &#39;userip&#39; =&gt; (string) $_REQUEST[&#39;ip&#39;],
            &#39;firstname&#39; =&gt; (string) $_REQUEST[&#39;firstname&#39;],
            &#39;lastname&#39; =&gt; (string) $_REQUEST[&#39;lastName&#39;],
            &#39;email&#39; =&gt; (string) $_REQUEST[&#39;email&#39;],
            &#39;password&#39; =&gt; (string) $_REQUEST[&#39;password&#39;],
            &#39;phone&#39; =&gt; (string) $_REQUEST[&#39;phonenumber&#39;],
            &#39;prefix&#39; =&gt; (string) $_REQUEST[&#39;phonecode&#39;],
        ))
    ));

... and here

    do {
        $mrc = curl_multi_exec($mh, $active);
    } while ($mh == CURLM_CALL_MULTI_PERFORM);

you&#39;re checking the wrong value, $mh is NEVER CURLM_CALL_MULTI_PERFORM , you want to compare it to $mrc, not $mh
(also CURLM_CALL_MULTI_PERFORM has been removed by the libcurl developers because so many people used it wrong, and that happened years ago, it&#39;s no longer needed in modern code.)

in addition to that, i don&#39;t like the way you implemented the loop at all.. try this instead:

    while (1) {
        do {
            $mrc = curl_multi_exec($mh, $active);
        } while ($mrc == CURLM_CALL_MULTI_PERFORM);
        if (!$active) {
            break;
        }
        curl_multi_select($mh);
    }


but with all that said, i believe your real problem is that you run curl_multi_remove_handle() &amp; curl_multi_close() BEFORE you call curl_multi_getcontent().

