In XSLT/XPATH numbers must use a full-stop as the decimal indicator, not a comma as is used in some cultures. It can also not contain any currency symbols (See https://www.w3.org/TR/xpath-10/#NT-Number)

So, you will need to remove any currency symbol or space from your element, and then convert to the number. If your values is limited to what it contains, you can do this

    &lt;xsl:value-of select=&quot;number(translate(MaxTaxFreeValue, &#39;,€ &#39;, &#39;.&#39;)) 
                            + number(translate(Reduction, &#39;,€ &#39;, &#39;.&#39;))&quot; /&gt;

Note the use of `+` here, not `-`. If you subtract a negative number from another number, then this is the same as adding the positive version of that number, so I think you actually need addition here if `Reduction` is always going to be negative.

See http://xsltfiddle.liberty-development.net/94AbWAN as an example. Note that this only works with the Euro currency symbol, and also assumes the elements are non-empty. 

On the other hand, if you want to handle any unexpected symbols, or if the elements may be empty, you probably need to create a named template to do the conversion, as you would need to do more work with a double-translate:

    &lt;xsl:template name=&quot;convertToNumber&quot;&gt;
      &lt;xsl:param name=&quot;element&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;xsl:choose&gt;
          &lt;xsl:when test=&quot;normalize-space($element)&quot;&gt;
              &lt;xsl:value-of select=&quot;translate($element, concat(&#39;,&#39;, translate($element, &#39;-01234567890&#39;, &#39;&#39;)), &#39;.&#39;)&quot; /&gt;
          &lt;/xsl:when&gt;
          &lt;xsl:otherwise&gt;0&lt;/xsl:otherwise&gt;
      &lt;/xsl:choose&gt;
    &lt;/xsl:template&gt;

The nested translate will return the non-numeric characters in the string, which is then used to remove them from the main string.

Then, you can make use of variables, which call this template, to do the calculation

    &lt;xsl:variable name=&quot;maxTaxFreeValue&quot;&gt;
        &lt;xsl:call-template name=&quot;convertToNumber&quot;&gt;
            &lt;xsl:with-param name=&quot;element&quot; select=&quot;MaxTaxFreeValue&quot; /&gt;
        &lt;/xsl:call-template&gt;
    &lt;/xsl:variable&gt;
    &lt;xsl:variable name=&quot;reduction&quot;&gt;
        &lt;xsl:call-template name=&quot;convertToNumber&quot;&gt;
            &lt;xsl:with-param name=&quot;element&quot; select=&quot;Reduction&quot; /&gt;
        &lt;/xsl:call-template&gt;
    &lt;/xsl:variable&gt;
    &lt;xsl:value-of select=&quot;number($maxTaxFreeValue) + number($reduction)&quot; /&gt;

See http://xsltfiddle.liberty-development.net/94AbWAN/1 for an example of this

Of course, if you could use XSLT 2.0, you could use a function instead of a named template, along with the `replace` statement.

    &lt;xsl:function name=&quot;my:convertToNumber&quot; as=&quot;xs:decimal&quot;&gt;
      &lt;xsl:param name=&quot;element&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;xsl:value-of select=&quot;if (normalize-space($element)) then replace(replace($element, &#39;,&#39;, &#39;.&#39;), &#39;[^\.\-0-9]&#39;, &#39;&#39;) else 0&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;/xsl:function&gt;

See http://xsltfiddle.liberty-development.net/94AbWAN/2 for an example of this.

